com.gl.vn.me.ko.pies.base.doc

Annotation Type Defaults


  • @Documented
 @Retention(value=CLASS)
 @Target(value=PACKAGE)
public @interface Defaults
    Specifies rules that are applied to a package.

    The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT", "SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" here and in all packages annotated with this annotations are to be interpreted as described in RFC 2119.

    Default properties of all classes, interfaces, methods and constructors in the package:

    1. Classes SHOULD be treated mutable and not thread-safe unless otherwise is explicitly specified (Immutable and ThreadSafe annotation SHOULD be used for this purpose).
    2. Arguments and return values of methods MUST be non-null unless otherwise is explicitly specified. It SHOULD be specified by the ParametersAreNonnullByDefault annotation on package/class and/or by Nullable/ Nonnull annotations on fields/local variables/methods.
    3. Methods and constructors MUST NOT modify modifiable* objects passed as arguments unless otherwise is explicitly specified.
    4. Modifications of modifiable objects returned from methods MUST NOT affect the state of the object on which the method is invoked unless otherwise is explicitly specified. E.g. modification of contents of a List returned from someObject.getList() method MUST NOT affect state of the someObject.
    5. If a method returns an object that is supposed to be modifiable the object MUST be modifiable unless otherwise is explicitly specified.
    6. Enumeration, Iterable, Stream, array arguments and return values MUST NOT contain null elements unless otherwise is explicitly specified.
    7. Enumeration, Iterable, Stream, array arguments and return values SHOULD NOT contain duplicate elements (see Object.equals(Object)) unless otherwise is explicitly specified. In some obvious cases an explicit specification MAY be omitted (for example in case of a byte[]).
    8. Any timeouts MUST be interpreted as approximate periods of real time. See Object.wait(long) for that "more or less" phrase.
    9. One SHOULD remember that format of Strings returned by any method that overrides Object.toString() MAY be changed at any time unless the format is explicitly specified in the method specification.

    * Here and in any package annotated with Defaults we distinguish immutable and unmodifiable Java objects. Unmodifiable object (aka read-only object) is an object that is not intended to be modified via its API (modifiable object is the opposite), but it still MAY change its observable state. E.g. object returned by Collections.unmodifiableCollection(java.util.Collection) can't be modified via it's API, but because such an object is just a view of an actual Collection, its observable state MAY be modified. Immutable object is an object which observable state can't be changed once you have a reference to the object. Observable state of an immutable object can't even be changed because of publication via data race), and because of this immutable objects are inherently thread-safe just as specified by Immutable annotation.
